cel()\\nos.Exit(1)  // ← any non-nil error, including SilentError, triggers exit code 1\\n```\\n\\n## Fix\\n\\nChange `lifecycle.go:181` from `return NewSilentError(strategy.ErrEmptyRepository)` to `return nil`.\\n\\nThe log message already communicates the skip. Returning nil gives exit code 0, which is the correct behavior for a hook that successfully decided \\\"nothing to do.\\\"\\n\\n## File to Modify\\n\\n| File | Change |\\n|------|--------|\\n| `cmd/entire/cli/lifecycle.go:181` | `return NewSilentError(...)` → `return nil` |\\n\\n## Verification\\n\\n```bash\\nmise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci\\n```\\n\\nThen test in the Kiro IDE with an empty repo — the stop hook should exit 0 with no error.\\n\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"894bd488-2ccf-465c-b036-0b476ad3db90\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alisha/Projects/wt/kiro-oneshot\",\"sessionId\":\"75dc86c1-99d8-40a8-ba1e-018fbe0b4e9c\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"alisha/kiro-oneshot\",\"slug\":\"recursive-giggling-reef\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_013zSApsDmLTGsrZfXQBFZDr\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"\\n\\n`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\\nThis is a classic \\\"benign skip vs error\\\" distinction in CLI tools. When a hook decides \\\"nothing to do\\\" (e.g., empty repo), that's a successful execution — exit code 0. Returning a `SilentError` suppresses the error message but still triggers `os.Exit(1)` in `main.go`, which downstream tools (like Kiro IDE) interpret as failure. The fix is simple: return `nil` instead, since the log message already documents the skip.\\n`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`\\n\\nLet me read the file and make the change.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":22828,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":31684,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_token